{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Famous Impostors | image = File:FamousImpostors.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[Bram Stoker]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | genre = | publisher = [[Sidgwick & Jackson]] | release_date = 1910 | media_type = Print (hardcover) }}
'''''Famous Impostors''''' is the fourth and final book of [[non-fiction]] by [[Bram Stoker]] (the author of ''[[Dracula]]''), published in 1910.<ref>http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/s/bram-stoker/ Stoker's Biography at Fantastic Fiction.</ref> It is a book that deals with exposing various [[impostor]]s and [[hoax]]es.
==Contents== *Pretenders ** [[Perkin Warbeck]] ** The Hidden King ([[Sebastian of Portugal]]) ** Stephan Mali ([[Šćepan_Mali]]) ** [[Louis_XVII_of_France#Lost_Dauphin_claimants|The False Dauphins]] ** [[Olivia Serres|Princess Olive]] *Practitioners of Magic ** [[Paracelsus]] ** [[Cagliostro]] ** [[Mesmer]] *[[Wandering Jew|The Wandering Jew]] *[[John Law (economist)|John Law]] *Witchcraft and Clairvoyance ** [[Witches]] ** [[John Dee|Doctor Dee]] ** [[La Voisin]] ** Sir [[Edward Kelley]] ** [[Mother Damnable]] ** [[Matthew Hopkins]] *[[Arthur Orton]] (Tichborne claimant) *[[Cross-dressing|Women as Men]] ** The Motive for Disguise ** [[Hannah Snell]] ** [[La Maupin]] ** Mary East *Hoaxes, Etc. ** Two London Hoaxes (includes the [[Berners Street hoax]]) ** The Cat Hoax (a scam to buy cats brought to a certain address) ** The Military Review (a false parade announced at 1812) ** The Toll-Gate (a practical joke played by [[Charles Mayne Young]] for not paying a toll) ** The Marriage Hoax (a marriage stopped by the false claim that the groom already had a wife and children) ** Buried Treasure (a false treasure unearthed by a victim and a swindler, which gives his share to the victim in exchange for something of value) ** [[Dean Swift]]'s Hoax (an alleged letter written by a criminal about his accomplices and hideouts) ** Hoaxed Burglars (thieves steal a secure box containing lead) ** Bogus Sausages (sausages are discovered to be skins filled with bread) ** [[Great Moon Hoax|The Moon Hoax]] *[[Chevalier d'Eon]] *[[Political_decoy#Queen_Elizabeth_I_and_the_Bisley_Boy|The Bisley Boy]]
==Online texts== *[http://www.bramstoker.org/nonfic/04impostors.html Bram Stoker Online] Full PDF version of ''Famous Impostors''.
